44:25.530 --> 44:27.331 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And I think that doesn't go
away.

44:27.365 --> 44:28.900 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The world doesn't grieve when
you're grieving.

44:28.933 --> 44:30.935 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The world goes on about its
business.

44:30.968 --> 44:34.238 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You're having a good day and I'm
having a
bad one and vice versa.

44:34.272 --> 44:36.741 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And they could be very good and
very bad at
the same time.

44:36.774 --> 44:42.980 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that's -- you multiply that
by seven billion
and you have one element of
human experience.

44:43.014 --> 44:46.617 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: That's an
interesting way of
looking at life, the world.

44:46.651 --> 44:47.618 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
KENNETH LONERGAN: It's true.

44:47.652 --> 44:48.619 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
But it's true.

44:48.653 --> 44:50.521 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You can't think for seven
billion people.

44:50.555 --> 44:52.857 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And you can't put yourself in
positions of
the seven billion people.

44:52.890 --> 44:56.994 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But you can certainly stretch a
little bit
and put yourself in a few
hundred other people's

44:57.028 --> 44:58.829 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
place, I would hope.

44:58.863 --> 45:02.533 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: So then what's
the job of a
writer in that, when you think
about the world

45:02.567 --> 45:04.235 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
that way?

45:04.268 --> 45:06.637 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KENNETH LONERGAN: One job that
you have is
to notice patterns that only you
notice.

45:06.671 --> 45:12.310 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A writer, a director or an actor
or any artist
or creative person is who is
re-representing

45:12.343 --> 45:17.515 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
life through their work is, I
think, describing
the patterns that they see.

45:17.548 --> 45:28.759 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: In "Manchester By
the Sea,"
Lonergan knows he's fortunate to
be working

45:28.793 --> 45:32.964 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
with great actors, include
Michelle Williams,
giving life to his words.

45:32.997 --> 45:34.865 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MICHELLE WILLIAMS, Actress: I
really kept
in touch with Joe.

45:34.899 --> 45:36.567 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's been kind of weird for me
not seeing
Patrick.

45:36.601 --> 45:37.835 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
CASEY AFFLECK: I knew that.

45:37.868 --> 45:39.604 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MICHELLE WILLIAMS: Oh, OK, I
didn't know.

45:39.637 --> 45:41.872 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
CASEY AFFLECK: You could see him
if you want.

45:41.906 --> 45:44.008 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MICHELLE WILLIAMS: Could we ever
have lunch?

45:44.041 --> 45:46.944 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KENNETH LONERGAN: You have a
version in your
head that works.

45:46.978 --> 45:50.181 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And then the actors come, and
that's what
I would say would be...

45:50.214 --> 45:51.916 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And they mess it
up or they
do it...

45:51.949 --> 45:53.784 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

45:53.818 --> 45:55.620 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KENNETH LONERGAN: Well, if
they're not seeing
all the elements in the scene
that I can see,

45:55.653 --> 45:57.955 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
then I will try to point them
out.

45:57.989 --> 46:01.993 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Once they understand the scene
at least as
well as I did, they then go much
further.

46:02.026 --> 46:05.730 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And they become the characters,
whereas I
only imagine the characters.

46:05.763 --> 46:10.835 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And when it's Casey and
Michelle, I really
expect and get, like, way more
than I -- than

46:10.868 --> 46:12.603 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I think that I put in.

46:12.637 --> 46:15.773 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And when you have people like
this, you're
-- sometimes, you just sit back
and watch

46:15.806 --> 46:17.508 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
them go.

46:17.541 --> 46:20.745 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that's just -- that is why
you become
a director, or why you become a
playwright

46:20.778 --> 46:26.484 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
or a screenwriter, is to see
actors do that
with your -- with what you
imagined initially

46:26.517 --> 46:29.654 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in your little room some time
two or three
years ago.

46:29.687 --> 46:31.589 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And it's just beautiful.

46:31.622 --> 46:35.626 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
