46:58.215 --> 47:03.454 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Tonight, we hear from inmates at
California's
San Quentin Prison who committed
crimes when

47:03.487 --> 47:06.624 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
they were young and are serving
up to life
terms.

47:06.657 --> 47:11.395 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
They're part of a weekly
discussion group
where they focus on
self-improvement through

47:11.429 --> 47:13.497 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
discussion, education, and
counseling.

47:13.531 --> 47:19.170 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The program is part of a larger
collaboration
with the design firm IDEO and
the California

47:19.203 --> 47:23.941 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Department of Corrections to
develop prisons
that support the
transformational growth of

47:23.974 --> 47:25.743 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
incarcerated young men.

47:25.776 --> 47:31.916 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAN: I have been incarcerated
for first-degree
murder and robbery at the age of
17, and I

47:31.949 --> 47:33.784 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
have been incarcerated for
almost 28 years.

47:33.818 --> 47:36.353 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MAN: I have been incarcerated
for the past
31 years.

47:36.387 --> 47:38.389 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I came here when I was 19 years
old.

47:38.422 --> 47:42.693 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MAN: At the age of 19, I
committed a robbery-murder
with two of my friends at the
time.

47:42.727 --> 47:44.695 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I am sentenced to 25 years
to life for
that.

47:44.729 --> 47:50.234 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MAN: I committed two
second-degree murders
at the age of 19, and I was
sentenced to 30

47:50.267 --> 47:52.036 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to life, plus 11.

47:52.069 --> 47:56.707 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MAN: At the age of 18, I
committed first-degree
murder in commission of a
robbery, and was

47:56.741 --> 47:57.875 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
sentenced to 25 years to life.

47:57.908 --> 48:00.377 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
MAN: I committed a
robbery-murder at the age
of 18.

48:00.411 --> 48:02.246 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I was sentenced to 25 years to
life.

48:02.279 --> 48:04.615 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
MAN: At the age of 16, I
committed my crime.

48:04.648 --> 48:11.255 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I handed my co-defendant a
loaded .38 special
pistol to commit a robbery, and
during the

48:11.288 --> 48:14.625 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
process of that robbery, a man
was shot and
killed.

48:14.658 --> 48:19.363 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAN: When I was 15, I committed
a crime of
first-degree murder, and I was
sentenced to

48:19.396 --> 48:20.998 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
25 years to life in prison

48:21.031 --> 48:24.702 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
QUESTION: What did it feel like
to receive
a life sentence at such a young
age?

48:24.735 --> 48:30.307 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAN: When somebody asked me,
hey, you know
how long do you got, and I would
say, I'm

48:30.341 --> 48:31.909 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
serving 25 years to life.

48:31.942 --> 48:34.945 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What they told me was that, just
get comfortable.

48:34.979 --> 48:40.217 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
You are never going home.

48:40.251 --> 48:50.294 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MAN: My father was an alcoholic
that used
to abuse my mother.

48:50.294 --> 48:55.332 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MAN: My father was an alcoholic
that used
to abuse my mother.

48:55.366 --> 48:58.803 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Later, she married my
stepfather, who was
also physically abusive.

48:58.836 --> 49:03.340 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAN: When I met my friend's
older brother
that was committing robberies, I
felt powerful

49:03.374 --> 49:07.945 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
doing that, when I felt
powerless at home
to stop my father abusing me and
my mother.

49:07.978 --> 49:10.214 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MAN: I'm originally from Laos.

49:10.247 --> 49:14.385 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Actually, I was born in a
refugee camp.

49:14.418 --> 49:16.120 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I joined a gang at 12 years old.

49:16.153 --> 49:20.090 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAN: I committed a gang-related
murder and
my mother and little brother was
killed in

49:20.124 --> 49:21.592 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
retaliation.

49:21.625 --> 49:25.229 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MAN: My grandfather was killed,
brutally murdered
when I was 10 years old.

49:25.262 --> 49:28.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
At that point, my innocence was
lost and I
begin to shut down.

49:28.966 --> 49:33.938 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAN: Having a dad that was in
and out of prison,
that was selling drugs and just
introducing

49:33.971 --> 49:37.007 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
me to a criminal lifestyle, that
was a big
part of it.

49:37.041 --> 49:43.848 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I feel like a bigger part of
it was finding
out that, when I was born, he
denied me.

49:43.881 --> 49:47.551 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think that was one of the
main things
that led to my committing my
crime.

49:47.585 --> 49:49.587 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MAN: A big part of my story is
coming to San
Quentin.

49:49.620 --> 49:52.656 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
San Quentin is a different
environment than
most prisons.

49:52.690 --> 49:58.729 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Being around men who were
telling their stories
allowed me to know that it was
OK to be vulnerable.

49:58.762 --> 50:01.365 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I hadn't talked about my crime
for almost
15 years.

50:01.398 --> 50:06.770 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAN: After being incarcerated
for 27 years,
I was open and honest about the
murder that

50:06.804 --> 50:08.505 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
I committed.

50:08.539 --> 50:11.575 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It was the looks of empathy, as
opposed to
looks of judgment, that created
the shift

50:11.609 --> 50:13.410 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in my mind-set.

50:13.444 --> 50:17.248 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAN: When I first started, I
wasn't able to
talk about myself, because I was
too embarrassed

50:17.281 --> 50:20.117 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and too ashamed to express the
things that
I have done.

50:20.150 --> 50:25.823 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MAN: It was hard in a
higher-level prison
to shed some of that
masculinity, the ideas

50:25.856 --> 50:30.828 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of masculinity and what I should
be and how
a criminal should act.

50:30.861 --> 50:33.964 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And then you come to a place
like San Quentin,
and it's a culture shock.

50:33.998 --> 50:39.236 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAN: I was wondering like,
what's in the water,
right, because the guys were so
super articulate

50:39.270 --> 50:42.840 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and well-spoken and showing much
insight into
themselves.

50:42.873 --> 50:47.878 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAN: I started off with a
program called GRIP,
which stands for Granting Rage
in the Power.

50:47.912 --> 50:51.282 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It helped me develop emotional
intelligence
and cultivate the mindfulness.

50:51.315 --> 50:56.453 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAN: What really keeps me
motivated is this
program called SQUIRES, where I
am able to

50:56.487 --> 50:58.522 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
mentor the at-risk and neglected
youth.

50:58.555 --> 51:03.193 align:left position:25%,start line:73.33% size:75%
When I see this
14--to-15-year-old telling
me his story and I see myself in
that kid,

51:03.227 --> 51:05.930 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
it is easier for me to have that
conversation
with them.

51:05.963 --> 51:08.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
QUESTION: Do you ever think that
you could
relapse into crime?

51:08.799 --> 51:13.404 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAN: Well, based on the change
that I have
made now, there is no way that I
could find

51:13.437 --> 51:15.539 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
myself relapsing in a crime.

51:15.572 --> 51:21.211 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I'm not blaming my past for the
traumatic
experience, for the crimes that
I committed.

51:21.245 --> 51:27.184 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I do understand that it was
a contributing
factor to what I did, and I do
take total

51:27.217 --> 51:28.986 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
responsibility for it.

51:29.019 --> 51:30.721 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MAN: Catching a case looks like
this.

51:30.754 --> 51:35.125 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I'm walking down the street, and
then, all
of a sudden, it just falls out
the sky in

51:35.159 --> 51:36.126 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
my hand.

51:36.160 --> 51:37.227 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I made a choice to carry a
pistol.

51:37.261 --> 51:39.697 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I made a choice to commit harm
to another
person.

51:39.730 --> 51:42.666 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that's the difference
between catching
a case and saying committed my
crime.

51:42.700 --> 51:47.237 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAN: I was stuck at this point
where I only
committed a robbery, and I
didn't commit a

51:47.271 --> 51:48.672 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
murder.

51:48.706 --> 51:50.341 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
One of my co-defendants was the
actual one
who committed the murder.

51:50.374 --> 51:55.646 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A young man at the age of 19
lost his life
because of the actions that I
did.

51:55.679 --> 52:02.152 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
QUESTION: Do you think about
that crime still?

52:02.186 --> 52:08.392 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MAN: Yes, definitely, most
definitely.

52:08.425 --> 52:13.263 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, what I did when I was 15
years old, I
shattered a community.

52:13.297 --> 52:16.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I tore a family apart.

52:16.066 --> 52:19.036 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I was a taker, and I took a
life.

52:19.069 --> 52:22.006 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And so I do think about that
every time.

52:22.039 --> 52:24.441 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
QUESTION: What would you tell
your dad about
your life today?

52:24.475 --> 52:34.551 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAN: I would say, you know what,
thanks, pops,
for all that B.S. that you
instilled in me.

52:34.585 --> 52:40.824 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But I would tell him you know, I
get you.

52:40.858 --> 52:48.632 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Like, all that denying me, all
that irresponsibility,
I mean, you didn't know any
better.

52:48.665 --> 52:50.467 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I would say, you know what,
I forgive
you.

52:50.501 --> 52:56.340 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
QUESTION: What would you like to
tell somebody
at that same age about to commit
a violent...

52:56.373 --> 52:59.610 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MAN: You have value.

52:59.643 --> 53:01.045 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
You have importance.

53:01.078 --> 53:02.446 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
You matter in this world.

53:02.479 --> 53:06.984 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There is nothing that can come
between that
and yourself.

53:07.017 --> 53:09.420 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MAN: My name is Adnan (ph).

53:09.453 --> 53:10.587 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MAN: My name is Cleo (ph).

53:10.621 --> 53:12.156 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MAN: My name is Tommy Shakur
Ross (ph).

53:12.189 --> 53:13.357 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MAN: My name is Phillip Melendez
